Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Case called at 1:32 pm [Clerk SH]
[Reserve Judge Robert Mawdsley presiding for BrIV]
Defendant Gregory N Hawkins in court, in -custody, with Attorney Elizabeth F. Svehlek. DA Susan V. Happ appeared for the State of Wisconsin.

Court examines the Defendant as to rights, understanding & intent.  
Mr. Hawkins waives his right to Preliminary Hearing; the Court accepts this waiver and binds him over for Arraignment.
State files information; Arraignment-Service of the Information admitted; reading waived; maximum penalties recited

Constitutional rights given; plea of "Guilty" entered; factual basis stipulated; victim rights compliance verified; Court finds the plea has been entered freely, voluntarily, intelligently and accepts the plea, finds Defendant guilty, orders JOC entered.

Court sentences Defendant to:
--serve 90 days in Jefferson County Jail, with Huber/Work-Release privileges for employment & child care; to commence consecutive to any other sentence in being
--0 days credit for time already served given
--pay costs of $268 + $250 DNA Surcharge = $518; due in $50 increments per month beginning 9/1/14 and on the 1st day of the month thereafter until paid in full; non-payment results in a 21 day jail term with Huber privileges, consecutive
--To submit DNA Sample upon
